this unusual performance. Taking no more notice of her than 
if she had been a fly, Mr. Laurence talked on about Laurie‚Äôs 
lessons and teachers; and presently, as if the idea had just 
occurred to him, he said to Mrs. March‚Äî 

‚ÄúThe boy neglects his music now, and I‚Äôm glad of it, for he 
was getting too fond of it. But the piano suffers for want of 
use. Wouldn‚Äôt some of your girls like to run over, and 
practise on it now and then, just to keep it in tune, you 
