‚Äú| need it so much; I‚Äôm dreadfully in debt, and it won‚Äôt be 
my turn to have the rag-money for a month.‚Äù 

‚ÄúIn debt, Amy? What do you mean?‚Äù and Meg looked 
sober. 

‚ÄúWhy, | owe at least a dozen pickled limes, and | can‚Äôt pay 
them, you know, till | have money, for Marmee forbade my 
having anything charged at the shop.‚Äù 

‚ÄúTell me all about it. Are limes the fashion now? It used to 
be pricking bits of rubber to make balls;‚Äù and Meg tried to 
keep her countenance, Amy looked so grave and important. 


‚ÄúWhy, you see, the girls are always buying them, and 
unless you want to be thought mean, you must do it, too. It‚Äôs 
nothing but limes now, for everyone is sucking them in their 
desks in school-time, and trading them off for pencils, bead- 
rings, paper dolls, or something else, at recess. If one girl 
likes another, she gives her a lime; if she‚Äôs mad with her, she 
eats one before her face, and don‚Äôt offer even a suck. They 
treat by turns; and I‚Äôve had ever so many, but haven‚Äôt 
returned them; and | ought, for they are debts of honor, you 
know.‚Äù 

‚ÄúHow much will pay them off, and restore your credit?‚Äù 
asked Meg, taking out her purse. 

‚ÄúA quarter would more than do it, and leave a few cents 
