Jo let Laurie win the game, to pay for that praise of her 
Beth, who could not be prevailed upon to play for them after 
her compliment. So Laurie did his best, and sung 
delightfully, being in a particularly lively humor, for to the 
Marches he seldom showed the moody side of his character. 
When he was gone, Amy, who had been pensive all the 
evening, said suddenly, as if busy over some new idea‚Äî 

