you; it isn‚Äôt proper,‚Äô said she, as sweet as honey. He tried to 
climb over the hedge, but it seemed to grow higher and 
higher; then he tried to push through, but it grew thicker 
and thicker, and he was in despair. So he patiently broke 
twig after twig, till he had made a little hole, through which 
he peeped, saying imploringly, ‚ÄòLet me in! let me in!‚Äô But the 
pretty princess did not seem to understand, for she picked 
her roses quietly, and left him to fight his way in. Whether 
he did or not, Frank will tell you.‚Äù 

‚ÄúI can‚Äôt; I‚Äôm not playing, | never do,‚Äù said Frank, dismayed 
at the sentimental predicament out of which he was to 
rescue the absurd couple. Beth had disappeared behind Jo, 
and Grace was asleep. 

‚ÄúSo the poor knight is to be left sticking in the hedge, is 
he?‚Äù asked Mr. Brooke, still watching the river, and playing 
with the wild rose in his buttonhole. 

‚Äú| guess the princess gave him a posy, and opened the 
gate, after a while,‚Äù said Laurie, smiling to himself, as he 
threw acorns at his tutor. 

‚ÄúWhat a piece of nonsense we have made! With practice 
we might do something quite clever. Do you know Truth?‚Äù 
asked Sallie, after they had laughed over their story. 


‚Äú| hope so,‚Äù said Meg soberly. 

‚ÄúThe game, | mean?‚Äù 

‚ÄúWhat is it?‚Äù said Fred. 

‚ÄúWhy, you pile up your hands, choose a number, and draw 
out in turn, and the person who draws at the number has to 
answer truly any questions put by the rest. It‚Äôs great fun.‚Äù 

‚ÄúLet‚Äôs try it,‚Äù said Jo, who liked new experiments. 

Miss Kate and Mr. Brooke, Meg, and Ned declined, but 
Fred, Sallie, Jo, and Laurie piled and drew; and the lot fell to 
Laurie. 

‚ÄúWho are your heroes?‚Äù asked Jo. 

‚ÄúGrandfather and Napoleon.‚Äù 

‚ÄúWhich lady here do you think prettiest?‚Äù said Sallie. 

‚ÄúMargaret.‚Äù 

‚ÄúWhich do you like best?‚Äù from Fred. 

‚ÄúJo, of course.‚Äù 

‚ÄúWhat silly questions you ask!‚Äù and Jo gave a disdainful 
shrug as the rest laughed at Laurie‚Äôs matter-of-fact tone. 

‚ÄúTry again; Truth isn‚Äôt a bad game,‚Äù said Fred. 

‚ÄúIt‚Äôs a very good one for you,‚Äù retorted Jo, in a low voice. 

Her turn came next. 

‚ÄúWhat is your greatest fault?‚Äù asked Fred, by way of 
testing in her the virtue he lacked himself. 

‚ÄúA quick temper.‚Äù 

‚ÄúWhat do you most wish for?‚Äù said Laurie. 

‚ÄúA pair of boot-lacings,‚Äù returned Jo, guessing and 
defeating his purpose. 

‚ÄúNot a true answer; you must say what you really do want 
most.‚Äù 

‚ÄúGenius; don‚Äôt you wish you could give it to me, Laurie?‚Äù 
and she slyly smiled in his disappointed face. 

‚ÄúWhat virtues do you most admire in a man?‚Äù asked Sallie. 

‚ÄúCourage and honesty.‚Äù 

‚ÄúNow my turn,‚Äù said Fred, as his hand came last. 

‚ÄúLet‚Äôs give it to him,‚Äù whispered Laurie to Jo, who nodded, 
and asked at once‚Äî 


‚ÄúDidn't you cheat at croquet?‚Äù 

‚ÄúWell, yes, a little bit.‚Äù 

‚ÄúGood! Didn‚Äôt you take your story out of The Sea-Lion?‚Äù 
Said Laurie. 

‚ÄúRather.‚Äù 

‚ÄúDon‚Äôt you think the English nation perfect in every 
respect?‚Äù asked Sallie. 

‚Äú| should be ashamed of myself if | didn‚Äôt.‚Äù 

‚ÄúHe‚Äôs a true John Bull. Now, Miss Sallie, you shall have a 
