‚ÄúHow beautifully you do it! | wish | could draw,‚Äù said Meg, 
with mingled admiration and regret in her voice. 

‚ÄúWhy don‚Äôt you learn? | should think you had taste and 
talent for it,‚Äù replied Miss Kate graciously. 

‚Äú| haven‚Äôt time.‚Äù 

‚ÄúYour mamma prefers other accomplishments, | fancy. So 
did mine; but | proved to her that | had talent, by taking a 
few lessons privately, and then she was quite willing | 
should go on. Can‚Äôt you do the same with your governess?‚Äù 

‚Äú| have none.‚Äù 


‚Äú| forgot; young ladies in America go to school more than 
with us. Very fine schools they are, too, papa says. You go to 
a private one, | suppose?‚Äù 

‚Äú| don‚Äôt go at all; | am a governess myself.‚Äù 

‚ÄúOh, indeed!‚Äù said Miss Kate; but she might as well have 
said, ‚ÄúDear me, how dreadful!‚Äù for her tone implied it, and 
something in her face made Meg color, and wish she had not 
