made Beth hate herself for her innocent blunder. 

‚ÄúYour deer are much prettier than our ugly buffaloes,‚Äù she 
said, turning to the prairies for help, and feeling glad that 
she had read one of the boys‚Äô books in which Jo delighted. 

Buffaloes proved soothing and satisfactory; and, in her 
eagerness to amuse another, Beth forgot herself, and was 
quite unconscious of her sisters‚Äô surprise and delight at the 
unusual spectacle of Beth talking away to one of the 
dreadful boys, against whom she had begged protection. 

‚ÄúBless her heart! She pities him, so she is good to him,‚Äù 
Said Jo, beaming at her from the croquet-ground. 

‚ÄúI always said she was a little saint,‚Äù added Meg, as if 
there could be no further doubt of it. 

‚Äú| haven‚Äôt heard Frank laugh so much for ever so long,‚Äù 
said Grace to Amy, as they sat discussing dolls, and making 
