was struck, hampers packed, wickets pulled up, boats 
loaded, and the whole party floated down the river, singing 
at the tops of their voices. Ned, getting sentimental, warbled 
a serenade with the pensive refrain‚Äî 


‚ÄúAlone, alone, ah! woe, alone,‚Äù 


and at the lines‚Äî 


‚ÄúWe each are young, we each have a heart, 
Oh, why should we stand thus coldly apart?‚Äù 


he looked at Meg with such a lackadaisical expression that 
she laughed outright and spoilt his song. 

‚ÄúHow can you be so cruel to me?‚Äù he whispered, under 
cover of a lively chorus. ‚ÄúYou‚Äôve kept close to that starched- 
up Englishwoman all day, and now you snub me.‚Äù 

‚Äú| didn‚Äôt mean to; but you looked so funny | really couldn‚Äôt 
help it,‚Äù replied Meg, passing over the first part of his 
