Vaughns were going to Canada. As the four sisters went 
home through the garden, Miss Kate looked after them, 
saying, without the patronizing tone in her voice, ‚ÄúIn spite of 
their demonstrative manners, American girls are very nice 
when one knows them.‚Äù 

‚Äú| quite agree with you,‚Äù said Mr. Brooke. 


XIII 


CASTLES IN THE AIR 


Laurie lay luxuriously swinging to and fro in his hammock, 
one warm September afternoon, wondering what his 
neighbors were about, but too lazy to go and find out. He 
was in one of his moods; for the day had been both 
unprofitable and unsatisfactory, and he was wishing he 
could live it over again. The hot weather made him indolent, 
and he had shirked his studies, tried Mr. Brooke‚Äôs patience to 
the utmost, displeased his grandfather by practising half the 
afternoon, frightened the maidservants half out of their wits, 
by mischievously hinting that one of his dogs was going 
mad, and, after high words with the stableman about some 
fancied neglect of his horse, he had flung himself into his 
hammock, to fume over the stupidity of the world in general, 
till the peace of the lovely day quieted him in spite of 
himself. Staring up into the green gloom of the horse- 
chestnut trees above him, he dreamed dreams of all sorts, 
and was just imagining himself tossing on the ocean, ina 
voyage round the world, when the sound of voices brought 
him ashore in a flash. Peeping through the meshes of the 
hammock, he saw the Marches coming out, as if bound on 
some expedition. 

‚ÄúWhat in the world are those girls about now?‚Äù thought 
Laurie, opening his sleepy eyes to take a good look, for there 
was something rather peculiar in the appearance of his 
neighbors. Each wore a large, flapping hat, a brown linen 
pouch slung over one shoulder, and carried a long staff. Meg 
had a cushion, Jo a book, Beth a basket, and Amy a portfolio. 
All walked quietly through the garden, out at the little back 


gate, and began to climb the hill that lay between the house 
and river. 

‚ÄúWell, that‚Äôs cool!‚Äù said Laurie to himself, ‚Äúto have a picnic 
and never ask me. They can‚Äôt be going in the boat, for they 
haven't got the key. Perhaps they forgot it; l'Il take it to 
them, and see what‚Äôs going on.‚Äù 

Though possessed of half a dozen hats, it took him some 
time to find one; then there was a hunt for the key, which 
was at last discovered in his pocket; so that the girls were 
quite out of sight when he leaped the fence and ran after 
them. Taking the shortest way to the boathouse, he waited 
for them to appear: but no one came, and he went up the 
hill to take an observation. A grove of pines covered one part 
of it, and from the heart of this green spot came a clearer 
sound than the soft sigh of the pines or the drowsy chirp of 
the crickets. 

‚ÄúHere‚Äôs a landscape!‚Äù thought Laurie, peeping through the 
bushes, and looking wide-awake and good-natured already. 

It was rather a pretty little picture; for the sisters sat 
together in the shady nook, with sun and shadow flickering 
over them, the aromatic wind lifting their hair and cooling 
their hot cheeks, and all the little wood-people going on with 
their affairs as if these were no strangers, but old friends. 
Meg sat upon her cushion, sewing daintily with her white 
hands, and looking as fresh and sweet as a rose, in her pink 
dress, among the green. Beth was sorting the cones that lay 
thick under the hemlock near by, for she made pretty things 
of them. Amy was sketching a group of ferns, and Jo was 
knitting as she read aloud. A shadow passed over the boy‚Äôs 
face as he watched them, feeling that he ought to go away, 
because uninvited; yet lingering, because home seemed 
very lonely, and this quiet party in the woods most 
attractive to his restless spirit. He stood so still that a 
squirrel, busy with its harvesting, ran down a pine close 
beside him, saw him suddenly and skipped back, scolding so 


shrilly that Beth looked up, espied the wistful face behind 
the birches, and beckoned with a reassuring smile. 

‚ÄúMay | come in, please? or shall | be a bother?‚Äù he asked, 
advancing slowly. 

Meg lifted her eyebrows, but Jo scowled at her defiantly, 
and said, at once, ‚ÄúOf course you may. We should have 
asked you before, only we thought you wouldn‚Äôt care for 
such a girl‚Äôs game as this.‚Äù 

‚ÄúI always liked your games; but if Meg doesn‚Äôt want me, l'Il 
go away.‚Äù 

‚ÄúI‚Äôve no objection, if you do something; it‚Äôs against the 
rules to be idle here,‚Äù replied Meg, gravely but graciously. 

‚ÄúMuch obliged; l'Il do anything if you‚Äôll let me stop a bit, 
for it‚Äôs as dull as the Desert of Sahara down there. Shall | 
sew, read, cone, draw, or do all at once? Bring on your bears; 
l'm ready,‚Äù and Laurie sat down, with a submissive 
expression delightful to behold. 

‚ÄúFinish this story while | set my heel,‚Äù said Jo, handing him 
the book. 

‚ÄúYes'm,‚Äù was the meek answer, as he began, doing his best 
to prove his gratitude for the favor of an admission into the 
Busy Bee Society. 

The story was not a long one, and, when it was finished, he 
ventured to ask a few questions as a reward of merit. 

‚ÄúPlease, ma‚Äôam, could | inquire if this highly instructive 
and charming institution is a new one?‚Äù 

‚ÄúWould you tell him?‚Äù asked Meg of her sisters. 

‚ÄúHe'll laugh,‚Äù said Amy warningly. 

‚ÄúWho cares?‚Äù said Jo. 

‚ÄúI guess he'll like it,‚Äù added Beth. 

‚ÄúOf course | shall! | give you my word | won't laugh. Tell 
away, Jo, and don‚Äôt be afraid.‚Äù 

‚ÄúThe idea of being afraid of you! Well, you see we used to 
play ‚ÄòPilgrim‚Äôs Progress,‚Äô and we have been going on with it 
in earnest, all winter and summer.‚Äù 

‚ÄúYes, | Know,‚Äù said Laurie, nodding wisely. 


‚ÄúWho told you?‚Äù demanded Jo. 

‚ÄúSpirits.‚Äù 

‚ÄúNo, | did; | wanted to amuse him one night when you 
were all away, and he was rather dismal. He did like it, so 
don‚Äôt scold, Jo,‚Äù said Beth meekly. 

‚ÄúYou can‚Äôt keep a secret. Never mind; it saves trouble 
now.‚Äù 

‚ÄúGo on, please,‚Äù said Laurie, as Jo became absorbed in her 
work, looking a trifle displeased. 

‚ÄúOh, didn‚Äôt she tell you about this new plan of ours? Well, 
we have tried not to waste our holiday, but each has had a 
task, and worked at it with a will. The vacation is nearly 
over, the stints are all done, and we are ever so glad that we 
didn‚Äôt dawdle.‚Äù 

‚ÄúYes, | should think so;‚Äù and Laurie thought regretfully of 
his own idle days. 

‚ÄúMother likes to have us out of doors as much as possible; 
SO we bring our work here, and have nice times. For the fun 
of it we bring our things in these bags, wear the old hats, 
use poles to climb the hill, and play pilgrims, as we used to 
do years ago. We call this hill the ‚ÄòDelectable Mountain,‚Äô for 
we can look far away and see the country where we hope to 
live some time.‚Äù 

Jo pointed, and Laurie sat up to examine; for through an 
opening in the wood one could look across the wide, blue 
river, the meadows on the other side, far over the outskirts 
of the great city, to the green hills that rose to meet the sky. 
The sun was low, and the heavens glowed with the splendor 
of an autumn sunset. Gold and purple clouds lay on the 
hilltops; and rising high into the ruddy light were silvery 
white peaks, that shone like the airy spires of some Celestial 
City. 

‚ÄúHow beautiful that is!‚Äù said Laurie softly, for he was quick 
to see and feel beauty of any kind. 

‚ÄúIt‚Äôs often so; and we like to watch it, for it is never the 
same, but always splendid,‚Äù replied Amy, wishing she could 


paint it. 

‚ÄúJo talks about the country where we hope to live some 
time‚Äîthe real country, she means, with pigs and chickens, 
and haymaking. It would be nice, but | wish the beautiful 
country up there was real, and we could ever go to it,‚Äù said 
Beth musingly. 

‚ÄúThere is a lovelier country even than that, where we shall 
go, by and by, when we are good enough,‚Äù answered Meg, 
with her sweet voice. 

‚ÄúIt seems so long to wait, so hard to do; | want to fly away 
at once, as those swallows fly, and go in at that splendid 
gate.‚Äù 

‚ÄúYou'll get there, Beth, sooner or later; no fear of that,‚Äù 
said Jo; ‚ÄúI‚Äôm the one that will have to fight and work, and 
climb and wait, and maybe never get in after all.‚Äù 

‚ÄúYou'll have me for company, if that‚Äôs any comfort. | shall 
have to do a deal of travelling before | come in sight of your 
Celestial City. If | arrive late, you'll say a good word for me, 
won‚Äôt you, Beth?‚Äù 

Something in the boy‚Äôs face troubled his little friend; but 
she said cheerfully, with her quiet eyes on the changing 
clouds, ‚ÄúIf people really want to go, and really try all their 
lives, | think they will get in; for | don‚Äôt believe there are any 
locks on that door, or any guards at the gate. | always 
imagine it is as it is in the picture, where the shining ones 
stretch out their hands to welcome poor Christian as he 
comes up from the river.‚Äù 

‚ÄúWouldn‚Äôt it be fun if all the castles in the air which we 
make could come true, and we could live in them?‚Äù said Jo, 
after a little pause. 

‚ÄúI‚Äôve made such quantities it would be hard to choose 
