XVII 


LITTLE FAITHFUL 


For a week the amount of virtue in the old house would have 
supplied the neighborhood. It was really amazing, for 
everyone seemed in a heavenly frame of mind, and self- 
denial was all the fashion. Relieved of their first anxiety 
about their father, the girls insensibly relaxed their 
praiseworthy efforts a little, and began to fall back into the 
old ways. They did not forget their motto, but hoping and 
keeping busy seemed to grow easier; and after such 
tremendous exertions, they felt that Endeavor deserved a 
holiday, and gave it a good many. 

Jo caught a bad cold through neglect to cover the shorn 
head enough, and was ordered to stay at home till she was 
better, for Aunt March didn‚Äôt like to hear people read with 
colds in their heads. Jo liked this, and after an energetic 
rummage from garret to cellar, subsided on the sofa to nurse 
her cold with arsenicum and books. Amy found that 
housework and art did not go well together, and returned to 
her mud pies. Meg went daily to her pupils, and sewed, or 
thought she did, at home, but much time was spent in 
writing long letters to her mother, or reading the 
Washington despatches over and over. Beth kept on, with 
only slight relapses into idleness or grieving. All the little 
duties were faithfully done each day, and many of her 
sisters‚Äô also, for they were forgetful, and the house seemed 
like a clock whose pendulum was gone a-visiting. When her 
heart got heavy with longings for mother or fears for father, 
she went away into a certain closet, hid her face in the folds 
of a certain dear old gown, and made her little moan and 


prayed her little prayer quietly by herself. Nobody knew 
what cheered her up after a sober fit, but everyone felt how 
sweet and helpful Beth was, and fell into a way of going to 
her for comfort or advice in their small affairs. 

All were unconscious that this experience was a test of 
character; and, when the first excitement was over, felt that 
they had done well, and deserved praise. So they did; but 
their mistake was in ceasing to do well, and they learned 
this lesson through much anxiety and regret. 

‚ÄúMeg, | wish you‚Äôd go and see the Hummels; you know 
mother told us not to forget them,‚Äù said Beth, ten days after 
Mrs. March‚Äôs departure. 

‚ÄúI‚Äôm too tired to go this afternoon,‚Äù replied Meg, rocking 
comfortably as she sewed. 

‚ÄúCan't you, Jo?‚Äù asked Beth. 

‚ÄúToo stormy for me with my cold.‚Äù 

‚ÄúI thought it was almost well.‚Äù 

‚ÄúIt‚Äôs well enough for me to go out with Laurie, but not well 
enough to go to the Hummels‚Äô,‚Äù said Jo, laughing, but 
looking a little ashamed of her inconsistency. 

‚ÄúWhy don‚Äôt you go yourself?‚Äù asked Meg. 

‚Äú| have been every day, but the baby is sick, and | don‚Äôt 
know what to do for it. Mrs. Hummel goes away to work, and 
Lottchen takes care of it; but it gets sicker and sicker, and | 
think you or Hannah ought to go.‚Äù 

Beth spoke earnestly, and Meg promised she would go 
tomorrow. 

‚ÄúAsk Hannah for some nice little mess, and take it round, 
Beth; the air will do you good,‚Äù said Jo, adding 
apologetically, ‚ÄúI‚Äôd go, but | want to finish my writing.‚Äù 

‚ÄúMy head aches and I‚Äôm tired, so | thought may be some of 
you would go,‚Äù said Beth. 

‚ÄúAmy will be in presently, and she will run down for us,‚Äù 
suggested Meg. 

‚ÄúWell, l'II rest a little and wait for her.‚Äù 


So Beth lay down on the sofa, the others returned to their 
work, and the Hummels were forgotten. An hour passed: 
Amy did not come; Meg went to her room to try on a new 
dress; Jo was absorbed in her story, and Hannah was sound 
asleep before the kitchen fire, when Beth quietly put on her 
hood, filled her basket with odds and ends for the poor 
children, and went out into the chilly air, with a heavy head, 
and a grieved look in her patient eyes. It was late when she 
came back, and no one saw her creep upstairs and shut 
herself into her mother‚Äôs room. Half an hour after Jo went to 
‚Äúmother‚Äôs closet‚Äù for something, and there found Beth 
sitting on the medicine chest, looking very grave, with red 
eyes, and a camphor-bottle in her hand. 

‚ÄúChristopher Columbus! What‚Äôs the matter?‚Äù cried Jo, as 
Beth put out her hand as if to warn her off, and asked 
quickly‚Äî 

‚ÄúYou've had the scarlet fever, haven‚Äôt you?‚Äù 

‚ÄúYears ago, when Meg did. Why?‚Äù 

‚ÄúThen l'Il tell you. Oh, Jo, the baby‚Äôs dead!‚Äù 

‚ÄúWhat baby?‚Äù 

‚ÄúMrs. Hummel‚Äôs; it died in my lap before she got home,‚Äù 
cried Beth, with a sob. 

‚ÄúMy poor dear, how dreadful for you! | ought to have 
gone,‚Äù said Jo, taking her sister in her arms as she sat down 
in her mother‚Äôs big chair, with a remorseful face. 

‚ÄúIt wasn‚Äôt dreadful, Jo, only so sad! | saw in a minute that it 
was sicker, but Lottchen said her mother had gone for a 
doctor, so | took baby and let Lotty rest. It seemed asleep, 
but all of a sudden it gave a little cry, and trembled, and 
then lay very still. | tried to warm its feet, and Lotty gave it 
some milk, but it didn‚Äôt stir, and | knew it was dead.‚Äù 

‚ÄúDon‚Äôt cry, dear! What did you do?‚Äù 

‚Äú| just sat and held it softly till Mrs. Hummel came with the 
doctor. He said it was dead, and looked at Heinrich and 
Minna, who have got sore throats. ‚ÄòScarlet fever, ma‚Äôam. 
Ought to have called me before,‚Äô he said crossly. 


Mrs. Hummel told him she was poor, and had tried to cure 
baby herself, but now it was too late, and she could only ask 
him to help the others, and trust to charity for his pay. He 
smiled then, and was kinder; but it was very sad, and | cried 
with them till he turned round, all of a sudden, and told me 
to go home and take belladonna right away, or I‚Äôd have the 
fever.‚Äù 

‚ÄúNo, you won't!‚Äù cried Jo, hugging her close, with a 
frightened look. ‚ÄúO Beth, if you should be sick | never could 
forgive myself! What sha// we do?‚Äù 

‚ÄúDon't be frightened, | guess | shan‚Äôt have it badly. | 
looked in mother‚Äôs book, and saw that it begins with 
