take some belladonna, and | feel better,‚Äù said Beth, laying 
her cold hands on her hot forehead, and trying to look well. 

‚ÄúIf mother was only at home!‚Äù exclaimed Jo, seizing the 
book, and feeling that Washington was an immense way off. 
She read a page, looked at Beth, felt her head, peeped into 
her throat, and then said gravely; ‚ÄúYou‚Äôve been over the 
baby every day for more than a week, and among the others 
who are going to have it; so I‚Äôm afraid you are going to have 
it, Beth. l'II call Hannah, she knows all about sickness.‚Äù 

‚ÄúDon‚Äôt let Amy come; she never had it, and | should hate 
to give it to her. Can‚Äôt you and Meg have it over again?‚Äù 
asked Beth, anxiously. 

‚ÄúI guess not; don‚Äôt care if | do; serve me right, selfish pig, 
to let you go, and stay writing rubbish myself!‚Äù muttered Jo, 
as she went to consult Hannah. 

The good soul was wide awake in a minute, and took the 
lead at once, assuring Jo that there was no need to worry; 
everyone had scarlet fever, and, if rightly treated, nobody 
died‚Äîall of which Jo believed, and felt much relieved as they 
went up to call Meg. 

‚ÄúNow I'll tell you what we'll do,‚Äù said Hannah, when she 
had examined and questioned Beth; ‚Äúwe will have Dr. Bangs, 
just to take a look at you, dear, and see that we start right; 


then we‚Äôll send Amy off to Aunt March‚Äôs, for a spell, to keep 
her out of harm‚Äôs way, and one of you girls can stay at home 
and amuse Beth for a day or two.‚Äù 

‚Äú| shall stay, of course; I‚Äôm oldest,‚Äù began Meg, looking 
anxious and self-reproachful. 

‚ÄúI shall, because it‚Äôs my fault she is sick; | told mother I'd 
do the errands, and | haven't,‚Äù said Jo decidedly. 

‚ÄúWhich will you have, Beth? there ain‚Äôt no need of but 
one,‚Äù said Hannah. 

‚ÄúJo, please;‚Äù and Beth leaned her head against her sister, 
with a contented look, which effectually settled that point. 

‚ÄúI'll go and tell Amy,‚Äù said Meg, feeling a little hurt, yet 
rather relieved, on the whole, for she did not like nursing, 
and Jo did. 

Amy rebelled outright, and passionately declared that she 
had rather have the fever than go to Aunt March. Meg 
reasoned, pleaded, and commanded: all in vain. Amy 
protested that she would not go; and Meg left her in despair, 
to ask Hannah what should be done. Before she came back, 
Laurie walked into the parlor to find Amy sobbing, with her 
head in the sofa-cushions. She told her story, expecting to 
be consoled; but Laurie only put his hands in his pockets 
and walked about the room, whistling softly, as he knit his 
brows in deep thought. Presently he sat down beside her, 
and said, in his most wheedlesome tone, ‚ÄúNow be a sensible 
little woman, and do as they say. No, don‚Äôt cry, but hear 
what a jolly plan I‚Äôve got. You go to Aunt March‚Äôs, and I'll 
come and take you out every day, driving or walking, and 
we'll have capital times. Won‚Äôt that be better than moping 
here?‚Äù 

‚Äú| don‚Äôt wish to be sent off as if | was in the way,‚Äù began 
Amy, in an injured voice. 

‚ÄúBless your heart, child, it‚Äôs to keep you well. You don‚Äôt 
want to be sick, do you?‚Äù 

‚ÄúNo, I‚Äôm sure | don‚Äôt; but I dare say | shall be, for I‚Äôve been 
with Beth all the time.‚Äù 


‚ÄúThat‚Äôs the very reason you ought to go away at once, so 
that you may escape it. Change of air and care will keep you 
well, | dare say; or, if it does not entirely, you will have the 
fever more lightly. | advise you to be off as soon as you can, 
for scarlet fever is no joke, miss.‚Äù 

‚ÄúBut it‚Äôs dull at Aunt March‚Äôs, and she is so cross,‚Äù said 
Amy, looking rather frightened. 

‚ÄúIt won‚Äôt be dull with me popping in every day to tell you 
how Beth is, and take you out gallivanting. The old lady likes 
me, and l'Il be as sweet as possible to her, so she won‚Äôt peck 
at us, whatever we do.‚Äù 

‚ÄúWill you take me out in the trotting wagon with Puck?‚Äù 

‚ÄúOn my honor as a gentleman.‚Äù 

‚ÄúAnd come every single day?‚Äù 

‚ÄúSee if | don‚Äôt.‚Äù 

‚ÄúAnd bring me back the minute Beth is well?‚Äù 

‚ÄúThe identical minute.‚Äù 

‚ÄúAnd go to the theatre, truly?‚Äù 

‚ÄúA dozen theatres, if we may.‚Äù 

‚ÄúWell‚ÄîI guess‚ÄîI will,‚Äù said Amy slowly. 

