which was a singularly fitting song for her:‚Äî 


‚ÄúHe that is down need fear no fall, 
He that is low no pride; 

He that is humble ever shall 
Have God to be his guide. 


‚Äúlam content with what I have, 
Little be it or much; 

And, Lord! contentment still | crave, 
Because Thou savest such. 


‚ÄúFullness to them a burden is, 
That go on pilgrimage; 

Here little, and hereafter bliss, 
Is best from age to age!‚Äù 


XXIII 


AuNT MARCH SETTLES THE QUESTION 


Like bees swarming after their queen, mother and daughters 
hovered about Mr. March the next day, neglecting 
everything to look at, wait upon, and listen to the new 
invalid, who was in a fair way to be killed by kindness. As he 
Sat propped up in a big chair by Beth‚Äôs sofa, with the other 
three close by, and Hannah popping in her head now and 
then, ‚Äúto peek at the dear man,‚Äù nothing seemed needed to 
complete their happiness. But something was needed, and 
the elder ones felt it, though none confessed the fact. 

Mr. and Mrs. March looked at one another with an anxious 
expression, as their eyes followed Meg. Jo had sudden fits of 
sobriety, and was seen to shake her fist at Mr. Brooke‚Äôs 
umbrella, which had been left in the hall; Meg was 
