Teddy certainly had done it that time, for the babies were 
‚ÄúDaisy‚Äù and ‚ÄúDemi‚Äù to the end of the chapter. 


XXIX 


CALLS 


‚ÄúCome, Jo, it‚Äôs time.‚Äù 

‚ÄúFor what?‚Äù 

‚ÄúYou don‚Äôt mean to say you have forgotten that you 
promised to make half a dozen calls with me today?‚Äù 

‚ÄúI‚Äôve done a good many rash and foolish things in my life, 
but | don‚Äôt think | ever was mad enough to say I‚Äôd make six 
calls in one day, when a single one upsets me for a week.‚Äù 

‚ÄúYes, you did; it was a bargain between us. | was to finish 
the crayon of Beth for you, and you were to go properly with 
me, and return our neighbors‚Äô visits.‚Äù 

‚ÄúIf it was fair‚Äîthat was in the bond; and I stand to the 
letter of my bond, Shylock. There is a pile of clouds in the 
east; it‚Äôs not fair, and | don‚Äôt go.‚Äù 

‚ÄúNow, that‚Äôs shirking. It‚Äôs a lovely day, no prospect of rain, 
and you pride yourself on keeping promises; so be 
honorable; come and do your duty, and then be at peace for 
another six months.‚Äù 

At that minute Jo was particularly absorbed in 
dressmaking; for she was mantua-maker general to the 
family, and took especial credit to herself because she could 
use a needle as well as a pen. It was very provoking to be 
arrested in the act of a first trying-on, and ordered out to 
make calls in her best array, on a warm July day. She hated 
calls of the formal sort, and never made any till Amy 
compelled her with a bargain, bribe, or promise. In the 
present instance, there was no escape; and having clashed 
her scissors rebelliously, while protesting that she smelt 
thunder, she gave in, put away her work, and taking up her 


hat and gloves with an air of resignation, told Amy the 
victim was ready. 

‚ÄúJo March, you are perverse enough to provoke a saint! You 
don‚Äôt intend to make calls in that state, | hope,‚Äù cried Amy, 
surveying her with amazement. 

‚ÄúWhy not? I‚Äôm neat and cool and comfortable; quite proper 
for a dusty walk on a warm day. If people care more for my 
clothes than they do for me, | don‚Äôt wish to see them. You 
can dress for both, and be as elegant as you please: it pays 
for you to be fine; it doesn‚Äôt for me, and furbelows only 
worry me.‚Äù 

‚ÄúOh dear!‚Äù sighed Amy; ‚Äúnow she‚Äôs in a contrary fit, and 
will drive me distracted before | can get her properly ready. 
I‚Äôm sure it‚Äôs no pleasure to me to go today, but it‚Äôs a debt we 
owe society, and there‚Äôs no one to pay it but you and me. I'll 
do anything for you, Jo, if you'll only dress yourself nicely, 
