If Jo had only Known what a great happiness was wavering 
in the balance for one of them, she would have turned 
dovelike in a minute; but, unfortunately, we don‚Äôt have 
windows in our breasts, and cannot see what goes on in the 
minds of our friends; better for us that we cannot asa 
general thing, but now and then it would be such a comfort, 
such a saving of time and temper. By her next speech, Jo 
deprived herself of several years of pleasure, and received a 
timely lesson in the art of holding her tongue. 

‚Äú| don‚Äôt like favors; they oppress and make me feel like a 
Slave. I‚Äôd rather do everything for myself, and be perfectly 
independent.‚Äù 

‚ÄúAhem!‚Äù coughed Aunt Carrol softly, with a look at Aunt 
March. 


‚ÄúI told you so,‚Äù said Aunt March, with a decided nod to 
