Our FOREIGN CORRESPONDENT 


‚ÄúLondon. 
‚ÄúDEAREST PEOPLE‚Äî 
‚ÄúHere I really sit at a front window of the Bath 
Hotel, Piccadilly. It‚Äôs not a fashionable place, but 
uncle stopped here years ago, and won‚Äôt go 
anywhere else; however, we don‚Äôt mean to stay 
long, so it‚Äôs no great matter. Oh, | can‚Äôt begin to 
tell you how | enjoy it all! | never can, so l'Il only 
give you bits out of my notebook, for I‚Äôve done 
nothing but sketch and scribble since | started. 

‚Äú| sent a line from Halifax, when | felt pretty 
miserable, but after that | got on delightfully, 
seldom ill, on deck all day, with plenty of pleasant 
people to amuse me. Everyone was very kind to 
me, especially the officers. Don‚Äôt laugh, Jo; 
gentlemen really are very necessary aboard ship, 
to hold on to, or to wait upon one; and as they 
have nothing to do, it‚Äôs a mercy to make them 
useful, otherwise they would smoke themselves to 
death, I‚Äôm afraid. 

‚ÄúAunt and Flo were poorly all the way, and liked 
to be let alone, so when | had done what | could 
for them, | went and enjoyed myself. Such walks 
on deck, such sunsets, such splendid air and 
waves! It was almost as exciting as riding a fast 
horse, when we went rushing on so grandly. | wish 
Beth could have come, it would have done her so 
much good; as for Jo, she would have gone up and 


sat on the main-top jib, or whatever the high thing 
is called, made friends with the engineers, and 
tooted on the captain‚Äôs speaking-trumpet, she‚Äôd 
have been in such a state of rapture. 

‚ÄúIt was all heavenly, but | was glad to see the 
Irish coast, and found it very lovely, so green and 
