While apparently absorbed in her own affairs, Jo watched 
Beth; and, after many conflicting conjectures, finally settled 
upon one which seemed to explain the change in her. A 
slight incident gave Jo the clue to the mystery, she thought, 
and lively fancy, loving heart did the rest. She was affecting 
to write busily one Saturday afternoon, when she and Beth 
were alone together; yet as she scribbled, she kept her eye 
on her sister, who seemed unusually quiet. Sitting at the 
window, Beth‚Äôs work often dropped into her lap, and she 
leaned her head upon her hand, in a dejected attitude, while 
her eyes rested on the dull, autumnal landscape. Suddenly 


someone passed below, whistling like an operatic blackbird, 
and a voice called out‚Äî 

‚ÄúAll serene! Coming in tonight.‚Äù 

Beth started, leaned forward, smiled and nodded, watched 
the passerby till his quick tramp died away, then said softly, 
as if to herself‚Äî 

‚ÄúHow strong and well and happy that dear boy looks.‚Äù 
‚ÄúHum!‚Äù said Jo, still intent upon her sister‚Äôs face; for the 
bright color faded as quickly as it came, the smile vanished, 
and presently a tear lay shining on the window-ledge. Beth 

whisked it off, and glanced apprehensively at Jo; but she 
was scratching away at a tremendous rate, apparently 
engrossed in Olympia‚Äôs Oath. The instant Beth turned, Jo 
began her watch again, saw Beth‚Äôs hand go quietly to her 
eyes more than once, and, in her half-averted face, read a 
tender sorrow that made her own eyes fill. Fearing to betray 
herself, she slipped away, murmuring something about 
needing more paper. 

‚ÄúMercy on me, Beth loves Laurie!‚Äù she said, sitting down in 
her own room, pale with the shock of the discovery which 
she believed she had just made. ‚ÄúI never dreamt of such a 
thing. What will mother say? | wonder if he‚Äî‚Äù there Jo 
stopped, and turned scarlet with a sudden thought. ‚ÄúIf he 
shouldn‚Äôt love back again, how dreadful it would be. He 
must; l'Il make him!‚Äù and she shook her head threateningly 
at the picture of the mischievous-looking boy laughing at 
her from the wall. ‚ÄúOh dear, we are growing up witha 
vengeance. Here‚Äôs Meg married and a mamma, Amy 
flourishing away at Paris, and Beth in love. I‚Äôm the only one 
that has sense enough to keep out of mischief.‚Äù Jo thought 
intently for a minute, with her eyes fixed on the picture; 
then she smoothed out her wrinkled forehead, and said, with 
a decided nod at the face opposite, ‚ÄúNo, thank you, sir; 
you're very charming, but you‚Äôve no more stability than a 
