four small children, all crying more or less, hadn‚Äôt 
diverted my mind; for | amused myself by 
dropping gingerbread nuts over the seat every 
time they opened their mouths to roar. 

‚ÄúSoon the sun came out, and taking it as a good 
omen, | cleared up likewise, and enjoyed my 
journey with all my heart. 

‚ÄúMrs. Kirke welcomed me so kindly | felt at home 
at once, even in that big house full of strangers. 
She gave me a funny little sky-parlor‚Äîall she had; 
but there is a stove in it, and anicetableina 
sunny window, so I can sit here and write 
whenever | like. A fine view and a church-tower 
opposite atone for the many stairs, and | took a 
fancy to my den on the spot. The nursery, where | 
am to teach and sew, is a pleasant room next 
Mrs. Kirke‚Äôs private parlor, and the two little girls 
are pretty children‚Äîrather spoilt, | fancy, but they 
took to me after telling them ‚ÄòThe Seven Bad Pigs;‚Äô 
and I‚Äôve no doubt I shall make a model governess. 


‚Äúlam to have my meals with the children, if | 
