‚ÄúNow, sir, you won‚Äôt forget to come and see us, if you ever 
travel our way, will you? l'Il never forgive you if you do, for | 
want them all to know my friend.‚Äù 

‚ÄúDo you? Shall | come?‚Äù he asked, looking down at her 
with an eager expression which she did not see. 

‚ÄúYes, come next month; Laurie graduates then, and you‚Äôd 
enjoy Commencement as something new.‚Äù 

‚ÄúThat is your best friend, of whom you speak?‚Äù he said, in 
an altered tone. 

‚ÄúYes, my boy Teddy; I‚Äôm very proud of him, and should like 
you to see him.‚Äù 

Jo looked up then, quite unconscious of anything but her 
own pleasure in the prospect of showing them to one 
another. Something in Mr. Bhaer‚Äôs face suddenly recalled the 
fact that she might find Laurie more than a ‚Äúbest friend,‚Äù 
and, simply because she particularly wished not to look as if 
anything was the matter, she involuntarily began to blush; 
and the more she tried not to, the redder she grew. If it had 
not been for Tina on her knee, she didn‚Äôt Know what would 


have become of her. Fortunately, the child was moved to 
