farewell, a bunch of violets to keep her company, and, best 
of all, the happy thought‚Äî 

‚ÄúWell, the winter‚Äôs gone, and I‚Äôve written no books, earned 
no fortune; but I‚Äôve made a friend worth having, and l'Il try 
to keep him all my life.‚Äù 


XXXV 


HEARTACHE 


Whatever his motive might have been, Laurie studied to 
some purpose that year, for he graduated with honor, and 
gave the Latin oration with the grace of a Phillips and the 
eloquence of a Demosthenes, so his friends said. They were 
all there, his grandfather‚Äîoh, so proud!‚ÄîMr. and 

Mrs. March, John and Meg, Jo and Beth, and all exulted over 
him with the sincere admiration which boys make light of at 
the time, but fail to win from the world by any after- 
triumphs. 

‚ÄúI‚Äôve got to stay for this confounded supper, but | shall be 
home early tomorrow; you'll come and meet me as usual, 
girls?‚Äù Laurie said, as he put the sisters into the carriage 
after the joys of the day were over. He said ‚Äúgirls,‚Äù but he 
meant Jo, for she was the only one who kept up the old 
custom; she had not the heart to refuse her splendid, 
successful boy anything, and answered warmly‚Äî 

‚ÄúI'll come, Teddy, rain or shine, and march before you, 
playing ‚ÄòHail the conquering hero comes,‚Äô on a jews-harp.‚Äù 

Laurie thanked her with a look that made her think, ina 
sudden panic, ‚ÄúOh, deary me! | know he'll say something, 
and then what shall | do?‚Äù 

Evening meditation and morning work somewhat allayed 
her fears, and having decided that she wouldn‚Äôt be vain 
enough to think people were going to propose when she had 
given them every reason to know what her answer would be, 
she set forth at the appointed time, hoping Teddy wouldn‚Äôt 
