‚ÄúThank you; it isn‚Äôt what it should be, but you have 
improved it,‚Äù he added, as she snapped the silver bracelet 
on her wrist. 

‚ÄúPlease don‚Äôt.‚Äù 

‚ÄúI thought you liked that sort of thing?‚Äù 

‚ÄúNot from you; it doesn‚Äôt sound natural, and I like your old 
bluntness better.‚Äù 

‚ÄúI‚Äôm glad of it,‚Äù he answered, with a look of relief; then 
buttoned her gloves for her, and asked if his tie was straight, 
just as he used to do when they went to parties together, at 
home. 

The company assembled in the long salle a manger, that 
evening, was such as one sees nowhere but on the 
Continent. The hospitable Americans had invited every 
acquaintance they had in Nice, and, having no prejudice 
against titles, secured a few to add lustre to their Christmas 
ball. 


A Russian prince condescended to sit in a corner for an 
hour, and talk with a massive lady, dressed like Hamlet‚Äôs 
mother, in black velvet, with a pearl bridle under her chin. A 
Polish count, aged eighteen, devoted himself to the ladies, 
who pronounced him ‚Äúa fascinating dear,‚Äù and a German 
Serene Something, having come for the supper alone, 
roamed vaguely about, seeking what he might devour. 
Baron Rothschild‚Äôs private secretary, a large-nosed Jew, in 
tight boots, affably beamed upon the world, as if his 
master‚Äôs name crowned him with a golden halo; a stout 
Frenchman, who knew the Emperor, came to indulge his 
mania for dancing, and Lady de Jones, a British matron, 
adorned the scene with her little family of eight. Of course, 
there were many light-footed, shrill-voiced American girls, 
handsome, lifeless-looking English ditto, and a few plain but 
piquante French demoiselles; likewise the usual set of 
travelling young gentlemen, who disported themselves 
gayly, while mammas of all nations lined the walls, and 
smiled upon them benignly when they danced with their 
