Any young girl can imagine Amy‚Äôs state of mind when she 
‚Äútook the stage‚Äù that night, leaning on Laurie‚Äôs arm. She 
knew she looked well, she loved to dance, she felt that her 
foot was on her native heath in a ballroom, and enjoyed the 
delightful sense of power which comes when young girls first 
discover the new and lovely kingdom they are born to rule 
by virtue of beauty, youth, and womanhood. She did pity 
the Davis girls, who were awkward, plain, and destitute of 
escort, except a grim papa and three grimmer maiden aunts, 
and she bowed to them in her friendliest manner as she 
