she had christened‚Äî 


‚ÄúIN THE GARRET. 


‚ÄúFour little chests all in a row, 
Dim with dust, and worn by time, 

All fashioned and filled, long ago, 
By children now in their prime. 

Four little keys hung side by side, 
With faded ribbons, brave and gay 

When fastened there, with childish pride, 
Long ago, on a rainy day. 

Four little names, one on each lid, 
Carved out by a boyish hand, 

And underneath there lieth hid 
Histories of the happy band 

Once playing here, and pausing oft 
To hear the sweet refrain, 

That came and went on the roof aloft, 
In the falling summer rain. 


‚Äú‚ÄúMeg‚Äô on the first lid, smooth and fair. 
| look in with loving eyes, 
For folded here, with well-known care, 
A goodly gathering lies, 
The record of a peaceful life‚Äî 
Gifts to gentle child and girl, 
A bridal gown, lines to a wife, 
A tiny shoe, a baby curl. 
No toys in this first chest remain, 
For all are carried away, 
In their old age, to join again 
In another small Meg‚Äôs play. 
Ah, happy mother! well | know 
You hear, like a sweet refrain, 


Lullabies ever soft and low 
In the falling summer rain. 


‚Äú‚ÄòJo‚Äô on the next lid, scratched and worn, 
And within a motley store 
Of headless dolls, of schoolbooks torn, 
Birds and beasts that speak no more; 
Spoils brought home from the fairy ground 
Only trod by youthful feet, 
Dreams of a future never found, 
Memories of a past still sweet; 
Half-writ poems, stories wild, 
April letters, warm and cold, 
Diaries of a wilful child, 
Hints of a woman early old; 
A woman in a lonely home, 
Hearing, like a sad refrain‚Äî 
‚ÄòBe worthy love, and love will come,‚Äô 
In the falling summer rain. 


‚ÄúMy Beth! the dust is always swept 
From the lid that bears your name, 
As if by loving eyes that wept, 
By careful hands that often came. 
Death canonized for us one saint, 
Ever less human than divine, 
And still we lay, with tender plaint, 
Relics in this household shrine.‚Äî 
The silver bell, so seldom rung, 
The little cap which last she wore, 
The fair, dead Catherine that hung 
By angels borne above her door; 
The songs she sang, without lament, 
In her prison-house of pain, 
Forever are they sweetly blent 
With the falling summer rain. 


‚ÄúUpon the last lid‚Äôs polished field‚Äî 
Legend now both fair and true‚Äî 

A gallant knight bears on his shield, 
‚ÄòAmy,‚Äô in letters gold and blue. 

Within lie snoods that bound her hair, 
Slippers that have danced their last, 

Faded flowers laid by with care, 
Fans whose airy toils are past; 

Gay valentines, all ardent flames, 
Trifles that have borne their part 

In girlish hopes and fears and shames‚Äî 
The record of a maiden heart 

Now learning fairer, truer spells, 
Hearing, like a blithe refrain, 

The silver sound of bridal bells 
In the falling summer rain. 


‚ÄúFour little chests all in a row, 
Dim with dust, and worn by time, 
Four women, taught by weal and woe 
To love and labor in their prime. 
Four sisters, parted for an hour, 
None lost, one only gone before, 
Made by love‚Äôs immortal power, 
Nearest and dearest evermore. 
Oh, when these hidden stores of ours 
Lie open to the Father‚Äôs sight, 
May they be rich in golden hours, 
Deeds that show fairer for the light, 
Lives whose brave music long shall ring, 
Like a spirit-stirring strain, 
Souls that shall gladly soar and sing 
In the long sunshine after rain. 


‚ÄúJ. M.‚Äù 


‚ÄúIt‚Äôs very bad poetry, but | felt it when | wrote it, one day 
when I was very lonely, and had a good cry on a ragbag. | 
