XLVII 


HARVEST TIME 


For a year Jo and her Professor worked and waited, hoped 
and loved, met occasionally, and wrote such voluminous 
letters that the rise in the price of paper was accounted for, 
Laurie said. The second year began rather soberly, for their 
prospects did not brighten, and Aunt March died suddenly. 
But when their first sorrow was over‚Äîfor they loved the old 
lady in spite of her sharp tongue‚Äîthey found they had 
cause for rejoicing, for she had left Plumfield to Jo, which 
made all sorts of joyful things possible. 

‚ÄúIt‚Äôs a fine old place, and will bring a handsome sum; for of 
course you intend to sell it,‚Äù said Laurie, as they were all 
talking the matter over, some weeks later. 

‚ÄúNo, | don‚Äôt,‚Äù was Jo‚Äôs decided answer, as she petted the 
fat poodle, whom she had adopted, out of respect to his 
former mistress. 

‚ÄúYou don‚Äôt mean to live there?‚Äù 

‚ÄúYes, | do.‚Äù 

‚ÄúBut, my dear girl, it‚Äôs an immense house, and will take a 
power of money to keep it in order. The garden and orchard 
alone need two or three men, and farming isn‚Äôt in Bhaer‚Äôs 
line, | take it.‚Äù 

‚ÄúHe'll try his hand at it there, if | propose it.‚Äù 

‚ÄúAnd you expect to live on the produce of the place? Well, 
that sounds paradisiacal, but you'll find it desperate hard 
work.‚Äù 

‚ÄúThe crop we are going to raise is a profitable one;‚Äù and Jo 
laughed. 

‚ÄúOf what is this fine crop to consist, ma‚Äôam?‚Äù 


‚ÄúBoys. | want to open a school for little lads‚Äîa good, 
happy, homelike school, with me to take care of them, and 
Fritz to teach them.‚Äù 

‚ÄúThere‚Äôs a truly Joian plan for you! Isn‚Äôt that just like her?‚Äù 
cried Laurie, appealing to the family, who looked as much 
surprised as he. 

‚ÄúI like it,‚Äù said Mrs. March decidedly. 

‚ÄúSo do |,‚Äù added her husband, who welcomed the thought 
of a chance for trying the Socratic method of education on 
modern youth. 

‚ÄúIt will be an immense care for Jo,‚Äù said Meg, stroking the 
head of her one all-absorbing son. 

‚ÄúJo can do it, and be happy in it. It‚Äôs a splendid idea. Tell us 
all about it,‚Äù cried Mr. Laurence, who had been longing to 
lend the lovers a hand, but knew that they would refuse his 
